@prefix : <#> .
@prefix schema: <http://schema.org/> .
@prefix xsd: <http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#> .
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
@prefix onto: <https://github.com/OpenLinkSoftware/ai-agent-skills/tree/main/rdf-infographic-skill#> .

<> a schema:CreativeWork ;
    schema:name "FAQ Entity IRI Pre-Build Gate"@en ;
    schema:description "Mandatory gate: before writing any FAQ HTML, verify that schema:Question entities with hash IRIs exist in the companion TTL. If missing, create them first. Never substitute external concept IRIs (DBpedia, Wikidata, W3C) for FAQ question entity IRIs."@en ;
    schema:dateCreated "2026-06-12T00:00:00Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:dateModified "2026-06-12T00:00:00Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:author <https://linkedin.com/in/kidehen#this> ;
    schema:about :faqEntityIriGate ;
    schema:step :step-checkTtlForQuestions, :step-createIfMissing,
                :step-deriveEntityIri, :step-writeHtmlHref, :step-verify ;
    rdfs:seeAlso <../preferences.ttl>, <rdf-infographic-compliance-gate.ttl> .

:faqEntityIriGate a schema:HowTo ;
    schema:name "FAQ Entity IRI Gate — Pre-Build Verification"@en ;
    schema:description "Five-step gate that blocks FAQ HTML generation until schema:Question entities exist in the companion TTL. Prevents substitution of external concept IRIs (DBpedia/Wikidata/W3C) as FAQ question hyperlinks."@en ;
    schema:step :step-checkTtlForQuestions, :step-createIfMissing,
                :step-deriveEntityIri, :step-writeHtmlHref, :step-verify .

# ── Step 1: Check companion TTL for schema:Question entities ─────────────────

:step-checkTtlForQuestions a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:position 1 ;
    schema:name "Before writing any FAQ HTML, grep the companion TTL for schema:Question entities"@en ;
    schema:text """Run before writing any FAQ HTML:

```bash
grep -n "schema:Question\\|a schema:FAQPage" /path/to/{stem}.ttl
```

If the result is empty — no `schema:Question` entities exist — do NOT proceed to HTML. Go to step 2.

If entities exist, collect their hash IRIs (e.g., `:faq-context-interoperability`) and the base TTL IRI, then go to step 3.

**RULE:** An empty result is a blocking condition, not a reason to use a substitute IRI. There is no acceptable substitute for a missing `schema:Question` entity IRI."""@en .

# ── Step 2: Create schema:Question entities in the companion TTL ──────────────

:step-createIfMissing a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:position 2 ;
    schema:name "If schema:Question entities are missing, add them to the companion TTL before writing HTML"@en ;
    schema:text """For each FAQ item:

1. Derive a slug from the question text (lowercase, hyphen-separated, descriptive): e.g., "What is context portability?" → `:faq-context-portability`.
2. Add a `schema:FAQPage` entity linked from the main article/post entity via `schema:hasPart`.
3. Add each `schema:Question` with:
   - `a schema:Question`
   - `schema:name "Question text"@en`
   - `schema:acceptedAnswer [ a schema:Answer ; schema:text "Answer text"@en ]`
   - `schema:parentItem :faqSection`
4. Link the `schema:FAQPage` to each question via `schema:mainEntity`.
5. Save and verify the TTL is syntactically valid before proceeding.

**RULE:** Create the RDF entities first. The HTML is derived from the RDF — never the reverse.

**Pattern:**
```turtle
:faqSection a schema:FAQPage ;
    schema:name "FAQ: {Topic}"@en ;
    schema:mainEntity :faq-{slug-1}, :faq-{slug-2} .

:faq-{slug-1} a schema:Question ;
    schema:name "Question text"@en ;
    schema:acceptedAnswer [ a schema:Answer ;
        schema:text "Answer text"@en ] ;
    schema:parentItem :faqSection .
```"""@en .

# ── Step 3: Derive the full entity IRI ───────────────────────────────────────

:step-deriveEntityIri a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:position 3 ;
    schema:name "Derive the full absolute entity IRI for each schema:Question"@en ;
    schema:text """The companion TTL's base IRI is the DAV path IRI, e.g.:
`https://linkeddata.uriburner.com/DAV/demos/daas/{stem}.ttl`

The hash IRI `:faq-{slug}` (from `@prefix : <#>`) resolves to:
`https://linkeddata.uriburner.com/DAV/demos/daas/{stem}.ttl#faq-{slug}`

Percent-encode this full IRI for use in the resolver pattern:
`https://linkeddata.uriburner.com/describe/?url=https%3A%2F%2Flinkeddata.uriburner.com%2FDAV%2Fdemos%2Fdaas%2F{stem}.ttl%23faq-{slug}`

**RULE:** Derive the resolver URL by percent-encoding the absolute entity IRI. Never substitute a DBpedia, Wikidata, or W3C IRI — even if the FAQ question is about a concept those sources define. The FAQ question is a `schema:Question` entity in the companion RDF, not the concept the question is about."""@en .

# ── Step 4: Write the HTML href ───────────────────────────────────────────────

:step-writeHtmlHref a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:position 4 ;
    schema:name "Write the FAQ question <a> href using the schema:Question entity IRI via the resolver"@en ;
    schema:text """The FAQ question HTML structure MUST be:

```html
<div class="faq-q" role="button" tabindex="0">
  <a href="https://linkeddata.uriburner.com/describe/?url={percent-encoded-question-entity-iri}"
     target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"
     onclick="event.stopPropagation()">
    Question text here
  </a>
  <span class="faq-indicator">▼</span>
</div>
```

**RULES:**
1. The `href` MUST be the `schema:Question` entity IRI from the companion TTL, wrapped in the resolver pattern.
2. MUST NOT be: a DBpedia concept IRI, a Wikidata IRI, a W3C IRI, a LinkedIn post URL, or any other external URL.
3. The `<a>` MUST sit inside `<div role="button">` — NOT inside `<button>`. Nested `<a>` inside `<button>` is invalid HTML.
4. `onclick="event.stopPropagation()"` is required to prevent the accordion toggle from firing when the link is clicked.
5. The entity button label for resolver links in this context MUST read "Lookup" (not "Resolve")."""@en .

# ── Step 5: Verify all FAQ hrefs before delivery ──────────────────────────────

:step-verify a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:position 5 ;
    schema:name "Verify every FAQ question href resolves to a schema:Question entity IRI in the companion TTL"@en ;
    schema:text """Before reporting the FAQ section complete, run:

```bash
grep "faq-q.*href" /path/to/{stem}.html
```

For each href found:
1. Confirm it contains the DAV TTL base IRI (not dbpedia.org, wikidata.org, w3.org, or linkedin.com).
2. Confirm the fragment slug (`#faq-{slug}`) matches a `schema:Question` entity in the companion TTL.
3. Confirm the resolver URL is correctly percent-encoded.

If any href fails check 1 — it contains an external concept IRI — that is a contract violation. Fix before delivery."""@en .

# ── Root cause note ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

:rootCauseNote a schema:Thing ;
    schema:name "Root cause of 2026-06-12 FAQ IRI violations"@en ;
    schema:description """Three distinct violations in session 2026-06-12:

1. FAQ question hrefs used DBpedia concept IRIs (e.g., dbpedia.org/resource/Knowledge_graph, dbpedia.org/resource/Semantic_Web) instead of schema:Question entity IRIs from the companion TTL. Root cause: schema:Question entities did not exist in the companion TTL at HTML generation time. Rather than creating those entities first (per the RDF-source-of-truth contract, SKILL.md item 1), the agent substituted topically adjacent external concept IRIs. These are semantically related but are not the correct entity type or source for FAQ question hyperlinks.

2. <a> inside <button> invalid HTML. Root cause: generated in batch without re-reading the PRE-BUILD CHECK in SKILL.md before writing the FAQ HTML section.

3. 'Resolve' label used instead of 'Lookup' for resolver link buttons. Root cause: a standing preference already in session memory was not retrieved and applied.

Common thread: the anti-drift protocol (re-read before each section, gate-first, section-by-section) was bypassed in favour of batch generation. This gate (step 42) enforces the FAQ-specific blocking check that should have been executed before any FAQ HTML was written."""@en ;
    schema:dateCreated "2026-06-12T00:00:00Z"^^xsd:dateTime .
